<bold>DOI</bold>: 10.4103/2321-3868.134083</td></tr></tbody></table></table-wrap><fig id="Fig1"><label>Figure 1:</label><caption><p>Materials used for an improved pressure glove.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="41038_2014_20030146_Fig1" id="d30e276"/></fig></p><p>Another drawback of the conventional finger-closed gloves is the inconvenience in checking up and evaluating the circulation in the distal end of the finger (i.e., the fingertip).[<xref ref-type="bibr" rid="CR4">4</xref>]</p><p>To overcome this inconvenience, we made another modification of the traditional pressure gloves by cutting the distal end of each finger open, thereby allowing for easier inspection of the circulation in the fingertip by doctors [Figure <xref rid="Fig2" ref-type="fig">2</xref>].<fig id="Fig2"><label>Figure 2:</label><caption><p>The pressure glove with an additional pocket inserted by a shaped thermoplastic splint and an open window at the distal end of each finger.</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="41038_2014_20030146_Fig2" id="d30e295"/></fig></p></body><back><fn-group><fn><p>
